data: {"type": "text-delta", "id": "a6421689-4732-410a-a089-b408defc3da1", "delta": "For a Linux host running low on disk space, here are the **read-only checks** you should run first to diagnose the issue:\n\n### 1. **Overall Disk Usage**\n```bash\ndf -h\n```\nShows mounted filesystems, total/used/available space, and usage percentage.\n\n### 2. **Top-Level Directory Sizes**\n```bash\ndu -sh /* 2>/dev/null | sort -rh | head -20\n```\nIdentifies which top-level directories are consuming the most space.\n\n### 3. **Log Directory Analysis**\n```bash\ndu -sh /var/log/* 2>/dev/null | sort -rh | head -20\n```\nLogs are often the culprit. This shows the largest log files.\n\n### 4. **Inode Usage**\n```bash\ndf -i\n```\nChecks if you're running out of inodes (file count limit), not just disk space.\n\n### 5. **Large Files Search**\n```bash\nfind / -type f -size +100M 2>/dev/null | head -20\n```\nFinds files larger than 100MB across the system.\n\n### 6. **Check for Deleted but Open Files**\n```bash\nlsof +L1 2>/dev/null | head -20\n```\nShows files that are deleted but still held open by processes (common cause of \"missing\" space).\n\n### 7. **Temporary Directories**\n```bash\ndu -sh /tmp /var/tmp 2>/dev/null\n```\nTemp directories often accumulate large files.\n\n### 8. **Application-Specific Directories**\n```bash\ndu -sh /var/lib/* 2>/dev/null | sort -rh | head -20\n```\nCheck database directories, package caches, and application data.\n\n---\n\n**Quick Action**: If you have the host name, I can run these checks for you automatically using the **Health Check (Linux)** service or execute specific commands. Just provide the hostname or IP.\n\nWould you like me to:\n1. Run a full health check on a specific host?\n2. Execute one of these commands on a particular host?\n3. Search for existing cases/alerts about this host?"}

